```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char str[100]; // Assuming the string will not be longer than 99 characters + null terminator
    printf("Enter a string: ");
    fgets(str, sizeof(str), stdin); // Read the string including spaces

    int length = strlen(str);
    int start = 0;
    int end = length - 1;

    // Filter out non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    while (start < end) {
        // Move start forward until an alphanumeric character is found
        while (start < end && !isalnum(str[start])) {
            start++;
        }
        // Move end backward until an alphanumeric character is found
        while (start < end && !isalnum(str[end])) {
            end--;
        }

        // Convert both characters to lowercase for comparison
        if (tolower(str[start]) != tolower(str[end])) {
            printf("The entered string is not a palindrome.\n");
            return 0;
        }

        start++;
        end--;
    }

    printf("The entered string is a palindrome.\n");

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:
- **`fgets()`**: This function reads a line of text into the buffer `str`, including any spaces.
- **`strlen()`**: This function returns the length of the string.
- **`isalnum()`**: This function checks if a character is alphanumeric (letter or digit).
- **`tolower()`**: Converts a character to lowercase.
- **Two-pointer technique**: We use two pointers, one at the beginning (`start`) and one at the end (`end`) of the string. We move them towards each other, comparing characters at these positions, and skip non-alphanumeric characters.

